data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","sequence_number":495,"item_id":"msg_08e897619fe1c2b800693b6786c56c8190a285e54b95b3f257","output_index":4,"content_index":0,"text":"That depends on the context, but here are typical roles and capabilities a \"secondary agent\" can have in common multi-agent or system-architecture setups, with short examples:\n\n- Redundancy / failover\n  - Acts as a standby that takes over if the primary fails (automatic promotion, state sync).\n- Load balancing / scaling\n  - Shares or takes on work during peaks to reduce latency and prevent overload.\n- Monitoring and health checks\n  - Continuously checks system/primary-agent health and reports or triggers recovery.\n- Backup and data replication\n  - Maintains copies of state or logs so recovery is faster and data isn’t lost.\n- Specialized processing\n  - Handles specific subtasks (e.g., image preprocessing, analytics, caching) to offload the primary.\n- Delegation and task handoff\n  - Accepts delegated work from the primary (or from clients) based on policies or capacity.\n- Coordination and orchestration\n  - Coordinates workflows across multiple components or agents, enforcing ordering or dependencies.\n- Security and access control\n  - Enforces additional checks, auditing, or acts as a gatekeeper for sensitive operations.\n- Logging, auditing, and observability\n  - Collects telemetry and provides context for debugging and compliance.\n- Mediation / arbitration\n  - Resolves conflicts between agents (e.g., resource contention, conflicting commands).\n- Graceful degradation\n  - Provides reduced-functionality operation when the primary or parts of the system are impaired.\n- Testing, simulation and canarying\n  - Runs tests or canary tasks to validate changes before they reach the primary production path.\n\nConstraints and design decisions to consider\n- Autonomy level: fully autonomous secondary vs. human-in-the-loop changes how it acts.\n- Permissions & data access: what it can read/write affects capabilities (consistency vs. availability tradeoffs).\n- State synchronization: how state is replicated and how failover is handled (eventual vs. strong consistency).\n- Latency and resource limits: impacts which tasks are practical to offload.\n- Failure modes and recovery policies: decide promotion criteria, split-brain handling, and rollback strategies.\n\nIf you tell me the specific system or scenario (e.g., database replicas, microservice architecture, autonomous robots, virtual assistants), I can give a focused list of responsibilities, example designs, or suggested implementation patterns. Which context do you mean?","logprobs":[]}

